 Expand all



                  Take us back to the beginning. How did you get started?
                  



I started importing small brands in the early 90's, when snowboarding was first big on the scene. I was the first UK distributor for well known board brands like LibTech, Gnu and Ride, as well as Northwave snowboard boots, and a variety of clothing brands. Snowboarding was a new sport. I was the importer for the UK and spent quite a lot of time traveling to and from California, mostly dealing with US brands. Off the back of that, I got into fashion footwear through the Northwave brand that's based out of Italy and as such, spent quite a lot of time in Italy, where I learned about shoe manufacturing. I picked up the distribution for DuFFS skate shoes for the UK in the mid 90's, just after they launched. I then took on the European distribution and license for DuFFS apparel. I used to make DuFFS branded tees, sweats, jeans, bags, etc and sell them across Europe. Ultimately, it reached the point where our DuFFS business was bigger than the North American DuFFS business, and so we approached the owners and bought the brand from them in 2008.  That was a pretty trying time because that was just as the whole world went into global recession and meltdown! We fought our way through that, and we sold the brand in 2012 and then set Ridgemont up.

Stacy Lowery, co-founder of Ridgemont, was head of design for DuFFS, and an ex pro skateboarder. He went on his honeymoon to Costa Rica, hiking, and before going he wanted to buy some suitable shoes to go hiking in. All he could find were some ugly black or brown hiking boots that he didn't feel comfortable wearing, and so he approached me and said, "I think there's a niche market here for fashionable outdoor footwear." He then did some drawings, and I said it seemed like a good idea, and Ridgemont was born. This happened in 2012. We then took a year, we were just sort of checking the market thinking that maybe we just missed something and there were people doing it. It probably took another year to totally convince ourselves, and then we started working on our design towards the end of 2013.




                  Where have the last few years gotten you?
                  



Initially it's all about finding vendors that will make the product, it's designing and creating the brand, the brand aesthetic, all of which took a little bit of time. Just coming up with a name takes a lot more effort than you think it's going to. We both had experience manufacturing in the Far East, but we still had to find factories that could do the quality that we expected. That also took time, as well, as a lot of traveling to China. Once we found factories that we could work with and would work with us, because it's hard for startups to get into a good factory, we then developed the first range, which consisted of two boots and two shoes. Then we went to our first  trade show, Agenda, in Long Beach. It was just when the outdoor movement suddenly started becoming quite cool. There were a few other brands in a similar place as us; brands like Topo Designs and Poler Stuff, who are not reinventing the outdoor product, but trying to sort of drag it forward and make it a bit more aesthetically fashionable and pleasing. We launched at Agenda and we got a great response.

We also were approached by a few retailers; one of the key ones we work with is in San Francisco, called Huckberry. They saw the potential immediately. Some of the other more traditional retailers are much slower when it comes to trying something new. We have had to plug away at that, and that's what we've been doing for the last two and a half years.  We’ve been attending trade shows, visiting with retailers, letting them see that we're still here, still around. Now they're finally committing. We’ve just been picked up for next autumn by REI, which is the biggest outdoor chain in North America.

We have a mirror operation in Europe, because I'm English and know the UK & European market. We have a warehouse facility in California and  a warehouse facility in Southampton in the UK and dual websites: a US website working in US currency that supplies North America and Canada, and one based in the UK which supplies the UK and Europe. Whilst the websites were there originally for promotional purposes, we also had Shopify e-commerce shops attached to them, and the online shops have actually been outperforming our expectations. They've been growing steadily, which has been great. It confirms what we thought, that consumers like our stuff.  I'm not a retailer, I've been a wholesaler for twenty years and so it's been a bit of a learning curve, but I think we're doing a pretty good job of it. That's one area, once this financing goes through, that we'll invest some money into and develop further.




                  Who are your customers?
                  



Our customer, according to Google Analytics, is 25-55, ABC1, relatively affluent, disposable income, travels, has keen interest in outdoor pursuits whether that be hiking, camping, climbing, surfing, or skating. Very much an outdoor active person. They want to be able to walk the dog, go for a hike, or go camping on the weekend; throw the tent in the back of the pickup and drive off up to Yosemite or wherever, but then they could just as well wear the same shoes if they're going out for dinner or down to the park or to the office. It's an all purpose product, and that's what our customer wants.

They probably have a pair of Keen or a pair of Lowas or Salomon or similar, and then they'd probably have a pair of Vans or Converse for more casual wear. I know when we've done photo shoots, and on a couple of occasions we didn't have sizes for some of the guys, they wore Vans or Converse and their feet got shredded just on a 15 mile hike. They definitely need something. As a result, our product works very well for travellers. We get quite a lot of gap year students who are in between from college to university who go off traveling for 6 months. It's perfect for them, they're going to backpack so they only want to carry one pair of shoes.




                  Who are your competitors? What do you understand that they don’t get?
                  



Brands like Merrell, North Face, Timberland & New Balance are offering something similar, but they don't offer the same technical specifications that we do at the same price points. From an entry level, we offer  water resistant products right the way up to our top of the range styles, which are fully waterproof and  breathable. No one else really does that at our prices.  For that level of technical specification from other brands, you start getting into price points which are double ours, up in the $300 area.

Within skate shoes, and the lifestyle fashion market, where a lot of my background is, people are always looking for something new. Whereas traditionally in the outdoor market they're not necessarily looking for something new, they're looking for something reliable that they know and they trust.

We want to give them both something reliable that they know and trust but that is also fashionable.  Form and function.




                  Why will you win?
                  



There's always people that want to be different. They don't want to have what everyone else has, and those people always shy away from the big brands. That's something which I'm very aware of from my days of working in skate and surf; there are always people looking for something fresh.

Bigger brands are copying our aesthetic but they're not copying us from a performance point of view. They have a boot that looks similar to ours, but it just looks similar, it doesn't have a waterproof breathable liner, for example. It doesn't have all the extra features that we throw in, because they can't afford to do it. The big companies need a bigger margin because they're a bigger machine. They have a wholesale margin that is probably 20 or 30 percent bigger than ours because they need that to pay for all the offices and all the staff.

Stacy and I are both very keen on the performance of our footwear. That’s one of the fundamentals of Ridgemont; fashionable but functional outdoor footwear.  We are constantly improving the product, so we're already on the 3rd version of a couple of the shoes because we're finessing our offering.  Nobody else really puts into outdoor shoes or sneaker boots the features that we put in for the price we sell for.

 Performance, quality, the materials - we use the same leather tanneries that the Timberlands and the Wolverines do. Similarly, the factories we use also make for all the well known brands, too.  They are all gold registered eco/environmentally friendly factories to make sure that they recycle, repurpose and reuse wherever they can to protect the environment. The factories are all clean,  tidy and a great working space. They have to be like that because they have to compete with all of the electronics factories that are making for Apple/Samsung etc. To get the workers to come and work for the shoe factories, they have to provide the same sort of environment.




                  Can you talk more about the design and production process?
                  



Everything is made in southern China in gold rated environmentally friendly factories. They're in an area called Dongguan, which is a big shoe making area and also very big for electronics; Apple makes most of its products there. The Samsung factory is right around the corner from one of our factories. There are all very good quality and reliable vendors.

The design is majoritively done by Stacy.  With wholesale we would do two collections a year and work 12 to 18 months out.  Now that we're focussing on direct to consumer we can draw then sample a style and if we like to go straight to production.  Concept to retail in less than 6 months.  It's great to have that freedom to bring new styles to life so much quicker and not having to rely on the approval of the wholesale market before proceeding.  We're now aiming to bring out new styles every 3 months.

We've got various silhouettes that are working for us, so what we tend to do once we get a silhouette that's working well, for example Outback and Monty Hi, then we go vertically where we'll do different materials, different levels of waterproofness, and that way we vary the price offering. Trying to offer lots and lots of different patterns is obviously expensive because you have lots of development and mold costs.  But taking one style that you know works and then offering a variety of colours, materials etc is quicker and easier to execute.




                  How do you make money?
                  



We aim to set our retail prices based on min x4 landed cost.  $20 landed cost for $80 retail, $50 for $200 etc. a 75% gross margin. When we're wholesaling we're only going to be making around less than 50% before sales related costs, volume discounts and trade shows etc.  So in effect we have to sell x3+ pairs at wholesale to make the same amount of $ profit as one pair at retail. That's what is great about the economics with the direct to consumer sales, it's so much more profitable.

Because we're small we're flexible, and we can get the factories we work with to make as little as 300 pairs of a color for us, whereas standard factories want 2,400 pairs. As we grow, and we order more, we can increase our margins. There's definitely scope. We have a guy on the ground in China working for us. He already knows he can get better deals, he just needs to have volume coming through.

We also keep our overheads tight by using 3PL, (third party logistic) warehouses, so we don't have an on-going large financial responsibility - we just pay per unit for them to pick and pack and store, which is great. It means when you're busy it costs a little bit more, but when you're not busy it's a lot cheaper, you don't have a lot of staff sitting around running up a bill.




                  What ideas do you have for growth in the next 3 months? 12?
                  



Now that we are focussing on direct to consumer sales we are seeing steady growth in revenues.  Sales for 2016 doubled to $342,000 and Q1 2017 was 320% up on Q1 2016.  We are focussing on digital marketing, PR and print advertising to increase brand awareness and drive sales through our e-commerce site.  We're upgrading our website constantly and introducing more and more retail features to increase conversion rates and drive sales.

In addition we are introducing new styles and products on crowdfunding sites like Kickstarter and Indiegogo.  This gives us an opportunity to test market reaction to products before committing to manufacture.  We have several new shoe styles, some as collaborations with other brands to showcase, plus luggage and accessory projects.

We expect to grow revenues to $800k+ in 2017 and expand into other territories.  We already have a fledging following in Europe but we hope to grow that more and more over the next 12 months.  Once direct sales are $1m+ with a 70%+ margin then we will revisit wholesale. We have good nationwide retail partners in the US that are interested in working with us once our awareness has increased and we already have international interest from distributors in Europe, Asia & Australia.




                  What’s next for your business? Why are you raising money now?
                  



We've created the Ridgemont brand, and we know people love it when they find it. The conversion rate on our website is over 4%.  We need to continue to increase awareness to drive more people to our site.  To do that we are investing significantly in digital marketing through Facebook, Instagram & Google as well as traditional PR activities and we have plans to do some print marketing with direct to consumer catalogues and event attendance at festivals etc.

In addition we want to expand the offering of styles and colours and materials of footwear and branch into luggage, apparel and accessories.

To do both of these things we need to raise money, some will go to fund production, to be able to make Ridgemont shoes and product to sell, but the bulk of it will go into our marketing efforts. 




                  What’s been your largest challenge so far?
                  



The biggest headache has definitely been wholesale. The retailers visit us and see the new products and say, "I love it, but I just don't see a place for it in my store." You tend to get an older senior buyer, and then you get a younger assistant buyer. The assistant buyer is all over us saying, "We should stock this," and then the senior buyer is, "Oh, I'm not sure, I'm not sure." and then it doesn't happen.

That's been the frustration, which is why it has led us to now focus on the direct consumer.  By appealing directly to the consumers who support us and we know love the brand we can sidestep the retailer who isn't willing to commit yet and bring Ridgemont to it's core fans.




                  This is an unusual fundraising strategy. Why have you given your customers the chance to invest online via Wefunder?
                  



The main reason is because obviously banks are very asset-based when they want to lend money, which makes it quite hard as a small business because we don't have the assets to borrow against. Plus, we know how much our consumers love what we do, and we feel that they'll want us to succeed and if we can give them a good return on $100, $500 or $1,000 or whatever they feel comfortable investing with us plus some great perks, then they get the benefit of not just getting a great return but that they've done something and helped a company and philosophy move forward.




                  Can you tell us about the team?
                  



I'm the President/CEO (Alex Hall), and then there's my co-founder Stacy Lowery, he's the creative director. He's responsible for new products and also the look and feel of the brand. John Lacroix is our digital marketing guru and Stephen Tims is our head of operations and handles all of the logistics and makes sure everything is where it should be and gets sent to the right people. We also have Carlos, who despite his name is Chinese, and is based in Dongguan in southern China. He has 20+ years of manufacturing footwear for lots of well known brands and handles all our production.




                  What keeps you up at night about the business?
                  



The biggest frustration to date is that we haven't progressed as quickly as I expected. Accepting that wholesale is going to take longer than we expected and instead concentrating on direct to consumer in the short term has definitely helped us move forward again.  Once we have a solid base, we can revisit wholesale and we will have more brand awareness and it will be easier to make it a success. We've got something which we know is good, everyone I share it with tells me it's great, and we've never had a bit of bad press. We’ve maybe had 120 articles across loads of different publications that everyone tells us how wonderful the product is. Translating that from what we know is a great product into hard sales has been a big frustration but I am now confident we know our path and the recent changes are definitely paying dividends already.




                  What is your cash on hand and burn rate?
                  



As of 31 March 2017, the company had approximately $32K cash (or cash equivalents) and $117K of fully paid up inventory. It operates at a run rate of approximately $10K per month.







  
